Glenroy comprises an approximate area of 2,438 hectares rivalling the largest landholdings in the region. Comprising quality soils and level to undulating topography underpinned by favourable climate characteristics, Glenroy is well suited to a range of breeding/fattening and winter crop production enterprises.

Key Investment Highlights 


Scale 

Comprising 2,438* contiguous hectares of productive land well suited to a range of cropping and grazing enterprises. 
Topography & Soils 
Rising from gently undulating red and red brown earth soils to small areas of timbered ridges and low hilltops with an average elevation of 460* metres above sea level.


Diversity 

A diverse enterprise mix comprising 800* hectares of cultivation, 1,339* hectares of arable grazing land, the remaining land consists of timbered ridges, shelter and support area.


Location 

Located centrally to Dubbo, Wellington, Dunedoo and Mudgee in the Mid-Western region of New South Wales, Glenroy benefits from convenient access to a range of markets, services and amenities resulting in excellent comparative advantage in reduced freight/transport costs.


Water

Glenroy presents a rare opportunity to purchase a property with significant scale and production capability. The offering of a large scale landholding in the Dunedoo - Gulgong region is unprecedented in recent years with sales in the surrounding area rivalling the size of Glenroy scarce and seldom offered to the public market.

The heritage listed "Christians Minde Retreat" is situated on the eastern coast of Australia and is bordered by the Booderee National Park, on the shores of Sussex Inlet, in Jervis Bay Territory.

The property will be sold on a vacant possession basis.

'Christians Minde' is a rustic style guest house, which was erected in 1896 by the Ellmoos family and is set on 11 acres of grounds in Jervis Bay Territory.  A 50m stretch of water separates the Christians Minde retreat from the main town of Sussex Inlet.

Christians Minde retreat was the first guest house on the coast south between Sydney and Eden.  In the late 1940's the guest house was converted into self-contained units.  Today the property offers self-contained units situated on the shores of Sussex Inlet.

Accommodation provides for 5 units (guest houses) and a residence, undercover BBQ facilities, communal laundry, a common room with TV, the cemetery, and outbuildings including boat sheds, and other service buildings located on the waters edge, including Christians Minde, the jetty and boathouse.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
Warragundi Aggregation is a rare large scale mixed enterprise, consisting of cattle, sheep, water and cropping, on the banks of the Cudgegong River. Warragundi is conveniently located approx. 25mins* drive to the tourism hotspot of Mudgee and 15mins* to the historic township of Gulgong. The region is renowned for its rich agricultural land, cool climate wines, gourmet food and stunning natural landscapes. 

Warragundi provides a unique large land holding with outstanding water access and highly improved infrastructure. The current owners have done an excellent job in creating and shaping Warragundi to where it is today. There are plans in place for further development through ongoing fertiliser application, improved pastures and extending the irrigated cropping area. 

The aggregation is being offered to the market as a ‘Walk in Walk Out’ transaction allowing an immediate income stream, a turn-key business and seamless transition. The owners have done a lot of the hard work and now wish to simplify their work commitments. 

The strong history of fertiliser application, access to water and fodder crops has enabled Warragundi the enviable ability to maintain its core breeding herd during this extended dry period. The stock produced on Warragundi have an outstanding reputation and their weight gains are above average for the region. 

Pastures include; chicory, cocksfoot, fescue, phalaris, ryegrass, sub clover and white clover mix. The properties are planted with either a winter or summer dominant pasture depending on soil types.  

The average carrying capacity of the combined aggregation is approx. 1,400 breeders plus 2,500 Merino ewes or 25,000 DSE*. Top line genetics are sourced from reputable studs for the cattle herd. 

Some Key Property Attributes Include:
•  Three centre pivots covering approx. 90 hectares* (222 acres*)
•  Suitable for beef, wool, lambs, horses and cropping
•  1,014ML water licence to the Regulated Cudgegong River
•  Strong history of fertiliser, rotational cropping and weed control
•  Efficient central laneway system and subdivided paddocks
•  Excellent water infrastructure including river, creeks, dams and troughs
•  Large commercial farm business with good economies of scale
•  Excellent yards with all-weather accessibility and loading
•  Contemporary main residence with pool and games room
•  Significant investment in Solar for irrigation and power

It is very hard to find a property of this size and quality in the Mudgee region. Most properties of this scale and size are being subdivided to accommodate the high demand for rural lifestyle blocks. 

For further details please contact the exclusive agents.

CBRE Agribusiness is pleased to present for sale the Shenhua Watermark Farming Portfolio (the Portfolio), one of Australia’s most significant agricultural offerings located within the Liverpool Plains and New England regions of NSW, on the Eastern Seaboard of Australia.

Comprising a total land area of approximately 18,111* hectares, the Portfolio includes three aggregations referred to as Breeza 15,789* hectares, Barraba 1,114* hectares and Tambar Springs 1,208* hectares.
The Portfolio benefits from being both geographically dispersed and having a diversified commodity mix, including both dryland, irrigated row cropping and livestock grazing.

Key investment highlights include:

BREEZA: Curlewis/Breeza, New South Wales
•	Comprises a total land area of 15,786 * hectares (39,009ac*) currently utilised for dryland cropping (cereals, legumes and cotton) and beef cattle grazing with the opportunity to irrigate, benefited by a total of 1,823* ML water access licences. 
 
•	Estimated total carrying capacity of 106,000* Dry Sheep Equivalents (dse) plus 11,000* Wheat Tonne Equivalents (wte).

•	Improvements comprise approximately 35 dwellings and rural structures.

•	The area has an Annual Average Rainfall of 634mm with a Rainfall Reliability Index of 64%.

•	Located in the renowned Liverpool Plains region of New South Wales and approximately 24* lineal kilometres south-east of Gunnedah.


BARRABA: Lindesay, New South Wales
•	Two non-contiguous holdings known as “Aandra” and “Clonmeen””, comprising a total land area of 1,114* hectares (2,752*ac).

•	The land area is principally utilised for sheep and beef cattle production.

•	Estimated total carrying capacity of 5,000* Dry Sheep Equivalents (dse).

•	The area has an Annual Average Rainfall of 688mm with a Rainfall Reliability Index of 66%.

•	Located approximately 30km west of Barraba, and approximately 138* kilometres north of Gunnedah.


TAMBAR SPRINGS: Tambar Springs, New South Wales
•	Three non-contiguous holdings known as “Mt Erin”, “Currajong” and “Glendowda” within 2* lineal kilometres of each other, comprising a total land area of 1,208* hectares (2,985ac*).

•	Estimated total carrying capacity of 6,000* Dry Sheep Equivalents (dse).
 
•	Improvements comprise approximately five dwellings and rural structures, including numerous sheds and livestock handling facilities.

•	The area has an Annual Average Rainfall of 582mm with a Rainfall Reliability Index of 63%.

•	Located approximately 75* kilometres south-west of Gunnedah.

*approximately

Common.Strapline.Common.Text: SIGNIFICANT NEW SOUTH WALES AGRICULTURAL AGGREGATIONS

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
-Located 85km North West of Dubbo and 45km from Gilgandra provides easy access to all markets, services and amenities.
-1,776* hectares of predominantly Black, Grey and Brown Vertosols with 1,406* arable hectares.  170* hectares of cotton has been planted into an excellent moisture profile.
-Versaility is pronounced via a lucrative opportunity to mine areas of minimal agricultural value through the supply of sand for the local area building trade, DA has been granted for this activity.
-550mm summer dominant rainfall allows a wide variety of summer and winter cropping opportunities.
-Double frontage to the Oxley Highway, which is a Road Train route, provides easy access in all directions from the property.
-High quality structural and ancillary improvements ensuring ease of management.

Common.Strapline.Common.Text: High productive dryland cropping boasting versatility though off farm cash flow ventures

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
Located on the northern edge of the highly regarded Liverpool Plains region encompassing approximately 2,664 hectares of prime cropping land over 19 freehold Certificates of Title.

-Exceptional land holding of approximately 2,664 hectares comprising irrigated and dryland cropping enterprises in one of Australia's most prominent agricultural regions.
-Close proximity to Tamworth, a major regional centre in New South Wales providing ease of access to all markets, services and amenities.
-Three highly reliable sources of irrigation water place Longacres in a class of its own with regard to water security and supply.
-Approximately 85% arable with strategically designed water storages and other infrastructure occupying the balance of the area.
-Highly developed infrastructure allows efficient production and ease of management.
-The combination of climate and soils make the Carroll region some of the most productive cropping land in Australia, capable of producing a wide range of summer and winter crops.
-Subdivided into 40 paddocks provides an opportunity to implement a diverse range of crops reducing risk profile.

Common.Strapline.Common.Text: Prime Cropping Land in one of Australia's Most Prominent Agricultural Regions

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
LIFESTYLE, TOURISM, SUBDIVISION

CBRE, in conjunction with Pacific Palms Real Estate, is pleased to present Oyster Point to market. The property’s elevated position offers lake and beach views, allowing investors, land bankers and lifestyle opportunists to capitalise on the site’s unique location and future potential.

Oyster Point benefits from the following key attributes:

- Site area: 22 acres*
- Picturesque location surrounded by Wamwarra Creek and Smiths Lake
- Elevated position with views to Sandbar Beach and Cellito Beach
- Future residential land subdivision potential (STCA)
- Residential concept plan created for 22-27 lots
- Great Lakes DCP concept masterplan created for 59 community title dwellings and a community centre
- Strong ageing demographic and popular holiday house destination
- Potential 'glamping' site, a popular upcoming trend

The property will be offered for sale via public auction on Tuesday 24 October 2017 at 10.30am AEST at AuctionWORKS.

To experience a 360° aerial view of Oyster Point, please visit:
https://viewer.hangar.com/bYLmB5Vj

*Approximate

For further details please contact the listed selling agents.

LARGE SCALE CATTLE FINISHING & DRYLAND FARMING

CBRE Agribusiness is pleased to present for sale Ashleigh, a large-scale cattle finishing and dryland farming property located in the renowned Northern Slopes region.

Key features of the opportunity include:

•	Large scale cattle finishing & dryland farming platform comprising a total land area of 4,391Ha*, of which 3,292Ha* (74%) is arable

•	High quality soil types & reliable climatic characteristics (average annual rainfall of 683mm*)

•	Proven history of turning off 4,200* dry cattle utilising winter & summer fodder crops combined with improved & native pastures

•	Recent development provides current management the confidence that 5,000-6,000 dry cattle could be finished in a more normal season

•	Approximately $1,400,000* has been invested in an extensive high flow reticulated water system to 22 grazing cells allowing for efficient utilisation of the grazing area

•	Frontage to the Gwydir River provides further access to water and is not currently utilised

•	Well-developed structural improvements, including numerous dwellings, cattle yards (3), shearing sheds (3), grain storages (700* tonnes) & sundry structures

•	Located in the renowned Northern Slopes region approximately 14* km west of Warialda & 60* km east of Moree

Common.Strapline.Common.Text: LARGE SCALE CATTLE FINISHING & DRYLAND FARMING

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
LOCATION: Approximately 11 kilometres east of Walcha on the Emu Creek road and some 76 kilometres south of Armidale.

AREA: Approximately 471 hectares freehold.

ELEVATION & RAINFALL: Annual average rainfall of 770 millimetres, approximately 1,050 to 1,170 metres ASL.

SOIL & WATER: A good balance of soil types from heavier basalt soil running to lighter loamy trap type soil.  Topography is undulating.  Watered by permanent Emu and Boundary Creeks .  A pump on Emu Creek pumps to supply tanks and reticulates to numerous troughs.

STRUCTURAL IMPROVEMENTS: 
- Historic 5 bedroom homestead (circa 1907) 
- Brookmount Retreat is a recently renovated 3 bedroom cottage used in recent years as a farm stay accommodation facility
- 4 bay machinery shed (approximately 300 square metres)
- Workshop / machinery shed (approximately 260 square metres)
- Grain shed
- Store shed
- Hay shed
- Timber cattle yards with vet crush
- Fenced into 16 main paddocks.  
All fencing in good stockproof condition.

HISTORY & COMMENTS: 147 years of family ownership by the Gill family comes to an end with the sale of Brookmount.  Previously Brookmount was home to the Gianna Super Fine Merino Stud, which was sold around 2010.  It has traditionally been managed conservatively as a mixed cattle and sheep operation.  Some pasture improvement work has been carried out in recent years and fertiliser applied intermittently.  There is a great opportunity to increase productivity with further pasture development and fertiliser application. The western block of Approx 810 hectares, including the shearing shed and sheep yards has been recently sold by expressions of interest.

SALE PROCESS: Homestead block of approximately 471 hectares is for sale by private treaty with a price of $1,500,000.

CBRE Agribusiness in conjunction with Bob Jamieson Agencies is pleased to present for sale Inverell Station (the Property). The Property features fertile soils, quality improvements, efficient property layout and secure water sources; offering the complete high-rainfall grazing package in one of Australia's foremost districts.

HOMESTEAD
Inverell Station Homestead features a commanding two-storey brick residence set on an elevated site comprising four large bedrooms, three bathrooms with polished blackbutt timber floors, modern kitchen, open-plan family room, formal lounge and dining rooms, ducted air conditioning and wood fires combine to create a homestead of distinction. Inverell Station Homestead is set in 1.5* hectares stunning tranquil gardens, established trees and sweeping lawns with inground pool, tennis court and two-bedroom guest accommodation.

SCALE
Featuring a total land area of 1,758* hectares of quality soils suited to a range of cropping, fodder production and grazing enterprises showcasing the versatility of the Property.

PRODUCTIVE CABABILITY
In excess of 550* hectares has been sown to forage sorghum and oats which is establishing strongly following recent rainfall allowing a purchaser immediate production options. Historical production of 600* cows and followers with additional backgrounding when seasonal conditions permit

SOILS AND TOPOGRAPHY
Rising from alluvial river flats lining the Macintyre River and Swan Brook Creek through arable slopes comprising black self-mulching basalt soils to lightly timbered hills well suited to a breeding and fattening enterprise.

SECURE WATER SUPPLY
Water for livestock is secured by five* kilometres of Macintyre River and nine* kilometres of Swan Brook Creek frontage. An automated pumping system on the Macintyre River supplies an extensive reticulation system providing secure water availability.

ADDITIONAL ACCOMODATION AND OPERATIONAL IMPROVEMENTS
An additional historic four-bedroom homestead once owned by the founder of Inverell and additional managers residence provides alternative accommodation options for owners or staff. Operational improvements include three machinery sheds and two sets of steel cattle yards.

CLIMATE AND LOCATION
Located within the Northern Tablelands Region of New South Wales, five* linear kilometres north of Inverell providing potential subdivision options (subject to council approval).
The strategic location of the Property provides convenient access to a full range of markets, services and amenities.

Northern Tablelands is considered the premier grazing region of New South Wales, a deserved recognition on account of reliable, temperate climate

THE OFFERING
Inverell Station is offered for sale by Expression of Interest in-one-line or as separate assets closing Wednesday 8 April 2020 at 4.00pm Australian Eastern Daylight Time (AEDT). The individual offerings are outlined below:

Lot One: Inverell Station Homestead – Featuring two* hectares including the notable Inverell Station Homestead and gardens.

Lot Two: Inverell Station - Comprises 1,596* hectares quality soils featuring operational improvements and historic homestead built by the districts first settler. Double-frontage to Macintyre River and Swan Brook. Potential subdivision options (subject to council approval).

Lot Three: Inverell Station Homestead Block - Comprises 160* hectares of river flats with an exceptional four-bedroom brick veneer residence. Features three* kilometre frontage to the Macintyre River.

Expression of Interest has been extended due to travel restrictions. 

*approximately

Common.Highlight.Common.Text: Favourable Balance of Land & Soil Types

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
CBRE Agribusiness in conjunction with Bob Jamieson Agencies are pleased to present for sale the prized Inverell asset, Penrose (the Property). Suitable as a beef and lamb backgrounding and finishing enterprise, Penrose is a beautiful farm located 15* linear kilometres from the Inverell township.

Set in the renowned Macintyre Valley, Penrose homestead presents an idyllic retreat adjoining the Macintyre River. The Property offers extensive basalt soils, an excellent water supply and immediate production with an included new season crop. The existing 999 head cattle feedlot presents forward contracting opportunities and combines with the Property’s natural features presenting as an ideal family business.

SCALE
Featuring 529* hectares of quality soils well suited to a range of cropping, fodder and grazing enterprises showcasing the versatility of the Property.

PRODUCTIVE CAPABILITY
In excess of 264* hectares of fertile dryland cropping recently sown to millet and oats which is establishing strongly following heavy recent rainfall. Historical production of 600* steers with additional back-grounding when seasonal conditions permit

SOILS AND TOPOGRAPHY
Rising from alluvial river flats lining the Macintyre River through to gently undulating cropping comprising black self-mulching basalt soils to lightly timbered hills well suited to a fattening enterprise.

SECURE WATER SUPPLY
Water is secured by four* kilometres of Macintyre River frontage and secure 14 megalitres of Inverell Water Source Entitlement. The Property features a new electric pump located on the Macintyre River reticulating water to the house and gardens via a 22,730* litre tank. Stock water is supplied via bore equipped with a diesel pump to 110,000* litre tank supplying troughs throughout the property. Each paddock has access to water.

ACCOMMODATION AND OPERATIONAL IMPROVEMENTS
Numerous operational improvements have been constructed over the Property including a comfortable four-bedroom brick homestead, watering points, grain storage, machinery sheds, shearing shed and feedlot.

CLIMATE AND LOCATION
Located within the Northern Tablelands Region of New South Wales, 15* linear kilometres north of Inverell. The strategic location of the Property provides convenient access to a full range of markets, services and amenities.

Northern Tablelands is considered the premier grazing region of New South Wales, a deserved recognition on account of reliable, temperate climate.

Expression of Interest has been extended due to travel restrictions. 

*approximately

- A 240Ha* grazing and cropping enterprise located 24* lineal kilometres west of Grafton, New South Wales.

- Soils consist of well draining alluvial river flats conducive to quality cropping and horticultural pursuits.

- 160ML* water allocation underpinned by a 1.5* kilometre frontage to the picturesque Clarence River.

- Well-developed structural improvements including grain storage, machinery shed, cattle yards and fully renovated four-bedroom home with stunning views.

- Clear potential for further development through utilising irrigation water for cropping or converting arable grazing land to high-value farming.

- Currently operated as a mixed farming enterprise in conjunction with a Charolais Stud.
